docs.lead_paragraph: A new type of dirty trick has entered one of the most closely watched Senate races in the country. On Wednesday, an unidentified volunteer for Beto O’Rourke, the Texas Democrat who is running against Senator Ted Cruz, gained access to the campaign’s mass-texting system and sent a series of unauthorized messages to Mr. O’Rourke’s supporters.

headline.main: ‘Impostor’ Sent Texts to Beto O’Rourke Supporters, Campaign Says
headline.print_headline: Dirty Tricks, via Texts, Are Aimed at Texas Democrat in a Key Senate Race

docs.abstract: There are 122 women on the primary ballots for congressional and statewide executive offices this week.
docs.snippet: There are 122 women on the primary ballots for congressional and statewide executive offices this week.
docs.lead_paragraph: In a year that has broken records for the number of women running for office, the primaries in eight states this week might be considered Super Tuesday for female candidates. More of them will appear on ballots for congressional and statewide executive offices than on any other single primary day in 2018 — a total of 122 women.

headline.main: Win or Lose, Tuesday’s Primaries Are a Big Deal for Women

docs.lead_paragraph: TOPEKA, Kan. — On the same night that a special congressional election in Ohio proved too tight to call, one of the most competitive Republican primaries for governor this summer was also deadlocked early Wednesday, as Kansas’s most populous county struggled to tally its votes in the race between Kris W. Kobach and Gov. Jeff Colyer.

headline.main: In Kansas, Another Close Race, as Kobach and Colyer Remain Deadlocked
